    <subfield code="a">A more appropriate subtitle for this brief presentation might be: “Strong-coupling (SC) estimates by infrared (IR) extraction”, representing an application to high-energy physics of a new technique which should find uses in many other fields. This work is fairly new, having appeared in a linear combination of reprints and preprints by Françoise GUÉRIN, Thierry GRANDOU, Hing-Tong CHO, and myself, references 1–4. In addition, a few remarks will be made at the end of the talk concerning a new and simple way of approximating ordered exponentials (OEs), devised by M.-E. BRACHET and myself, references 5–7. This presentation will consist of a very brief overview of ideas and methods, treating the following subjects: 1. 1) Motivation (Why IR?) 2. 2) Sketch of the IR method for &lt; ψψ > 3. 3) Gauge invariance 4. 4) (QED)2 estimates of &lt; ψψ >/mf → 0; and an SU(N) - (QCD)2 estimate of the same quantity. 5. 5) An IR approach to gluonic (QCD)4 6. 6) Ordered exponentials in SC limits Before beginning, a few preliminary remarks may be appropriate: 1. (i) In two-dimensional QED and QCD, the coupling constant g and the fermion mass mf ≡ m both have dimensions of mass. The true, dimensionless coupling is therefore g/m; and the SC limit is then the same as the chiral limit. 2. (ii) We have focused attention on &lt; ψψ > as the simplest possible gauge-invariance quantity to estimate, and its chiral limit is of interest here only as a test of the SC/IR method. There exist easier ways to calculate the chiral limit of &lt; ψψ > in (QED)2! 3. (iii) Contrary to a certain lore, which has grown up around computer calculations, the quenched estimates of &lt; ψψ > described here are finite; they contain no singularities, IR or UV, of any sort. The reason is that, being in the continuum, they introduce no spurious IR cutoffs (such as the inverse of a finite-volume dimension); and they present no temptation to pass to the limit of zero fermion mass before removing that IR cutoff. This is discussed in Section VII of reference 1.</subfield>
